ProjectSummary.ProjectSummaryProjectDescription:
(All information in this project is fictitious - any resemblance to a real-world project is purely coincidental.)
The Eastern Bay Conservation Project (EBCP) is focused on working with the residents of Eastern Bay Village to help manage and conserve the marine resources of their traditional fishing grounds. Key partners on the project team include the residents of Eastern Bay Village, Eastern Bay NGO, and researchers from the local university. Our conservation targets are coral reefs, sharks, seagrass beds, mangroves, and seabirds. Major threats include unsustainable fishing by local people, invasive rats eating seabird eggs, and commercial shark finning operations. The project is implementing strategies to rid key breeding islets of rats, establish alternative income sources for local fishermen, and to liaise with an international conservation organization to combat the demand for shark fin soup. We are monitoring both the status of our conservation targets and the effectiveness of our conservation strategies. This project is funded by the Adaptive Management Foundation and the Island Development Bank.
ProjectSummary.ProjectSummaryProjectStatus: We are now in the 1st year of the second 3-year phase of this project. We are currently working on several key strategies as well as our monitoring plan. At this point, most of the important local stakeholders have bought into this project. The rat elimination strategy is going well, but the sustainable fishery strategy is struggling and needs some major attention. We have also struggled to figure out how to deal with the shark finning threat. We are now going to try a longshot strategy of working with a major advocacy group to reduce demand for shark fin soup.
ProjectSummary.ProjectSummaryNextSteps: Need to do the planning for the sustainable ocean fishery strategy. Also, need to continue to implement the rat elimination work. Don't you think so?

ConceptualModel.ConceptualModelDetails: The Eastern Bay Conservation Project (EBCP) is focused on working with the residents of Eastern Bay Village to help manage and conserve the marine resources of their traditional fishing grounds. Key partners on the project team include the residents of Eastern Bay Village, Eastern Bay NGO, and researchers from the local university. Our conservation targets are coral reefs, sharks, seagrass beds, mangroves, and seabirds. Major threats include unsustainable fishing by local people, invasive rats eating seabird eggs, and commercial shark finning operations. The project is implementing strategies to rid key breeding islets of rats, establish alternative income sources for local fishermen, and to liaise with an international conservation organization to combat the demand for shark fin soup.

ResultsChain.ResultsChainDetails: Monitoring by university researchers shows that rats are currently attacking nesting seabirds on key islands in Eastern Bay. The rats seem to have come on birding tour boats that visit the islands. Our strategy is to trap the existing rats on the islands and to mandate rat barriers on visiting tourboats. We assume this will solve the rat problem within 2 years.

One current threat is that local commercial fishers are using destructive blast fishing techniques within the Bay. We would like to try to develop a sustainable ocean fishery as a substitute for the fishing in the Bay. This will depend on a feasibility analysis, getting the fishers to switch, and helping them to find markets for the new fish. Ultimately, if they cannot get as much income from the Ocean Fishery as they do from fishing locally, we will not see the desired behavioral change.

ResultsChain.ResultsChainName: Campaign to Stop Shark Fin Soup
ResultsChain.ResultsChainDetails: We are trying to deal with the threat posed by illegal shark finning operations coming from the mainland. We have determined that we don't have ability to stop things on the supply end. So we are trying to work with partners to influence the demand side. Most of the shark fins from Eastern Bay seem to go to the Hong Kong market. So we wlll try to start a campaign to stop restaurants from serving shark fin soup in Hong Kong. This is a long-shot, but seems to be our only option.

ThreatReductionResult.ThreatReductionResultDetails: If we can reduce global demand for shark fins, the hope is that it will stop the shark finning operations here in Eastern Bay.

IntermediateResult.IntermediateResultName: Reduced Demand for Shark Fins in Hong Kong
IntermediateResult.IntermediateResultDetails: Most of the current harvest in Eastern Bay goes to Hong Kong, However, the main problem here is that even if we can reduce demand in Hong Kong, will demand from other markets still cause pressure in Eastern Bay?
The campaign will target the leading seafood restaurants in Hong Kong. We will encourage restaurants to join the campaign and pledge not to serve Shark Fin Soup. We will also target consumers.

Stress.StressDetails: Rats are eating the seabird eggs.

Goal.GoalDetails: Healthy mangrove forests covers at least 80% of the shoreline in the project site for the next 50 years.
Seagrass beds cover all ecologically appropriate areas in the project site by 2013.
By 2020, there are at least 500 & adult sharks of each of the two main species in the greater Eastern Bay region.

Goal.GoalName: Healthy Coral Reefs Across Eastern Bay
Goal.GoalDetails: By 2020, there are healthy coral reefs across all appropriate areas in Eastern Bay.
By 2013, there are healthy populations of all three nesting seabirds on the islands of Eastern Bay.
By 2020, coral reefs provide flood protection equal to 2010 baseline values.
By 2020, the human populations of Eastern Bay continue to get at least 75% of their protein needs from marine fisheries.

Objective.ObjectiveName: Reduce Demand for Shark Fins in Hong Kong
Objective.ObjectiveDetails: By 2010, demand for shark fin soup has been reduced by 70% in Hong Kong below 2005 levels.
By 2013, there are no more than 10 incidents per year of shark fishing boats illegally fishing in Eastern Bay.
By 2009, more than 50% of the seafood restaurants in Hong Kong are active participants in the "Stop Shark Fin Soup" campaign.
By 2009, rats have been completely eliminated from all breeding islands.

Objective.ObjectiveName: Boats Have Rat Barriers in Place
Objective.ObjectiveDetails: By June 2008, all tourist boats visiting the Eastern Bay Islands have state-of-the-art rat barriers in place.
Objective.ObjectiveComments: We are assuming at the moment that other non-tourism boats are not a problem for rat re-introductions. However, we may want to make sure RAT team boats do have barriers -- or it could potentially be very embarassing.

Objective.ObjectiveDetails: By 2010, all households in Eastern Bay Village make at least as much income from a sustainable ocean fishery as they make from unsustainable fishing techniques in 2007.
By 2010, local commercial fishing in the Bay has been reduced by 75% below 2007 levels.
By 2009, 75% of the local commercial fisherman currently fishing in Eastern Bay have switched to the new ocean fishery.
By 2009, markets for ocean fish caught by Eastern Bay Village fishers have been developed so that 85% of all fish caught can be profitably sold.

Indicator.IndicatorName: Numbers of rats caught in traps
Indicator.IndicatorDetails: The total number of rats caught in traps set out for one week for each island. We assume that we need three weeks of having no rats to have eliminated the population.
Indicator.IndicatorComments: This is a great measure because it is "automatically" generated from the trapping strategy itself. After the initial trapping, however, we will need to continue to set traps to make sure there are no re-introductions of rats. This will require some additional funds.
Indicator.IndicatorFutureStatusDetails: We want to get to 0 rats in each island.

Indicator.IndicatorDetails: Evidence of seabird nests suffering from rat predation. In particular, egg shells with rat teeth marks.
